    <div class="fc-section-head reveal">
      <div class="eyebrow-row">
        <span class="fc-eyebrow">The 12-month thesis</span>
      </div>
      <h2>How do we go from 170K to 1M households?</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="fc-framing reveal">
      <p class="quote">Many things that work at 170K households break at 1M.</p>
      <p class="tail">These are the four that matter most in the next 12 months.</p>
    </div>

    <article class="fc-problem reveal">
      <div class="pr-num">01</div>
      <h3 class="pr-title">Personalisation - the app treats 170K households the same way</h3>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/><line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/></svg>
          Problem
        </span>
        <p>
          <em class="c">"Today"</em> is editorially curated but identical for everyone. <em class="c">"Your usuals"</em> is a passive reorder list - no prediction, no neighbourhood intelligence, no individual feed. FirstClub sits on one of the richest behavioural datasets in Indian consumer commerce and uses <strong>almost none of it</strong> at the surface.
        </p>
        <div class="fc-callout">A browse experience that shows everyone the same content becomes repetitive by order 10.</div>
        <p>
          Unlike any competitor, FirstClub has a <strong class="k">structural data advantage</strong>: a concentrated user base in identifiable apartment societies. <em class="c">Community data, not just location data.</em>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M9 18l6-6-6-6"/></svg>
          Solution
        </span>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Personalised Home Page</strong> - dynamically composed per user. Category weights and featured brands respond to individual order and browse history. UX structure stays; content layer becomes personal.</li>
          <li><strong>ML-Powered "Your Usuals"</strong> - predictive replenishment engine. Curd every 5-7 days? Surface on day 5. Out of stock? Suggest a quality-matched substitute that passed the same ingredient bar.</li>
          <li><strong>Society-Level Recommendations</strong> - "Most ordered in your society this week." Social proof, discovery via trusted neighbours, club identity. An unfamiliar brand ordered by 40 families in your building does not feel unfamiliar anymore.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><line x1="12" y1="20" x2="12" y2="10"/><line x1="18" y1="20" x2="18" y2="4"/><line x1="6" y1="20" x2="6" y2="16"/></svg>
          Success Metrics
        </span>
        <p>
          Orders per month: personalised feed vs. control. Add-to-cart rate on ML "Your usuals" nudges vs. manual reorder. Conversion on society recommendations. Repeat-purchase rate on products discovered through society data.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="22 7 13.5 15.5 8.5 10.5 2 17"/><polyline points="16 7 22 7 22 13"/></svg>
          ROI
        </span>
        <p>
          1-2 added SKUs per basket = <strong class="k">₹150-300/order</strong>. At <strong>4+ orders/month × 170K households</strong>, a conservative <strong class="k">15% basket lift</strong> from personalisation is real GMV. Compounding value: stickiness - a product that learns you is structurally harder to replace.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="fc-problem reveal">
      <div class="pr-num">02</div>
      <h3 class="pr-title">Multi-city quality at scale is an unsolved product problem</h3>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/><line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/></svg>
          Problem
        </span>
        <p>
          Quality curation in Bengaluru is <em class="c">founder-led and manual</em> - blind tastings, personal supplier relationships, central checks. Right tool for 0 to 1. <strong>Hyderabad has just launched</strong> with 3 stores and a materially different food culture - biryani masala, mutton, Irani chai, local dairy. A Bengaluru-mirrored catalogue underperforms. But there is no infrastructure to run a Hyderabad-specific curation in parallel.
        </p>
        <div class="fc-callout">Founder-led curation is the right tool for proof of concept. It is the wrong tool for five cities simultaneously.</div>
        <p>
          Series B capital is explicitly for <strong>geographic expansion</strong>. If each new city needs the same leadership involvement as Bengaluru, expansion is the bottleneck. Inconsistent quality across cities damages national trust <em class="c">before it exists</em>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M9 18l6-6-6-6"/></svg>
          Solution
        </span>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Curation OS</strong> - internal product for supplier onboarding, blind-test scoring, ingredient compliance, catalogue approval per city. Lifts the work out of spreadsheets and WhatsApp. A team of 3-4 runs curation across cities <em class="c">simultaneously</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>Community Sourcing for Local Curation</strong> - "nominate a brand" for FirstClub members in each new city. They know local premium better than a Bengaluru-based team. 2-week response window. Converts engaged users into <em class="c">brand evangelists</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>Local Occasion Calendar</strong> - Hyderabad gets Eid and Bathukamma. Chennai gets Pongal. Mumbai gets Ganesh Chaturthi. Auto-surface city-specific collections rather than defaulting to Bengaluru's.</li>
          <li><strong>Dark Store Micro-Assortment</strong> - core SKUs stay fixed across stores; a portion flexes by neighbourhood data (tech park vs. multigenerational colony). Quality consistent; assortment locally relevant.</li>
          <li><strong>Quality Consistency Audits</strong> - quarterly spot-check re-tests of high-volume catalogue SKUs. The quality promise should not <em class="c">degrade silently</em> as supplier relationships age.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="pr-block">
        <span class="pr-label">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><line x1="12" y1="20" x2="12" y2="10"/><line x1="18" y1="20" x2="18" y2="4"/><line x1="6" y1="20" x2="6" y2="16"/></svg>
          Success Metrics
        </span>
